<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="303" type="mainText">
The material which can undoubtedly be assigned to the typical form of 
<taxonomicName class="Chilopoda" family="Lithobiidae" genus="Eupolybothrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lithobiomorpha" pageId="0" pageNumber="303" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="litoralis">E. litoralis</taxonomicName>
is certainly conspecific with the specimens Verhoeff has labelled &quot; 
<taxonomicName class="Chilopoda" family="Lithobiidae" genus="Lithobius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lithobiomorpha" pageId="0" pageNumber="303" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="fasciatus" subSpecies="graecus">Lithobius fasciatus graecus</taxonomicName>
&quot;, but since the latter may represent a geographical race they should be regarded as belonging to a distinct subspecies unless it can be shown that their distinctive character is altogether unstable.
</paragraph>
